$lang['How do you decode Hexadecimal?'] = 'E fa&#39;afefea ona e fa&#39;avasegaina le Hexadecimal?';
$lang['When it comes to decoding Hexadecimal, there are a few things you need to know. First, just like the decimal system, the hexadecimal system has 10 symbols (0-9) that represent numbers. However, in hexadecimal, these digits have values that are twice as large as their counterparts in the decimal system. So, while the number “10” is represented by the symbol “A” in hexadecimal, it would be equal to “10” in the decimal system.'] = 'A o&#39;o i le decoding Hexadecimal, e iai nai mea e tatau ona e iloa. Muamua, e pei lava o le decimal system, o le hexadecimal system e 10 faailoga (0-9) e fai ma sui o numera. Ae ui i lea, i le hexadecimal, o nei numera e iai faʻatauga e faaluaina le lapopoa nai lo o latou faʻatusa i le faiga tesi. O lea la, e ui o le numera &quot;10&quot; o loʻo faʻatusalia e le faʻailoga &quot;A&quot; i le hexadecimal, e tutusa ma le &quot;10&quot; i le faiga o le decimal.';
$lang['Similarly, after reaching 9 in Hexadecimal (represented by “F”), we start counting again at 10 (“10”). This pattern continues until we reach 15 (“1F”), at which point we reset back to 0 and begin counting again at 16 (“20”). This might sound confusing at first, but with a little practice, it will become second nature!'] = 'E fa&#39;apena fo&#39;i, pe a uma ona o&#39;o i le 9 i le Hexadecimal (fa&#39;atusaina e le “F”), tatou toe amata toe faitau ile 10 (“10”). O lenei mamanu e faʻaauau pea seia oʻo ina tatou oʻo i le 15 (&quot;1F&quot;), o le taimi lea tatou te toe faʻafoʻi ai i le 0 ma amata toe faitau ile 16 (&quot;20&quot;). Atonu e foliga fenumiai i le taimi muamua, ae o sina faataitaiga, o le a avea ma natura lona lua!';
